In the 5K event there were a lot fewer runners who were over the age of 75. In the 10 Mile event there was 11 runners aged over 75 compared to only 7 runners in the 5K event. The youngest in the 5K run was 6, however the youngest runner in the 10 Mile run was 11. The oldest runner in the 5K event was 92, however the oldest runner in the 10 Mile event was 85. This means that the 5K event had the oldest and youngest runner. The majority if runners in both the 5K event and the 10 Mile event were aged between 20 and 40. In the 5K event there were a lot less runners who attended, only 2519, compared to 17442 runners in the 10 Mile event.

# Write your code to answer exercise 2a here

ggplot(data = run17,
       mapping = aes(
         x = net_sec/60,
        y = event
       )) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  labs(
    x = "time to complete race (minutes)" ,
    y = "event" , 
    
    title = "The time it took the runners to complete the event"
  ) +
  facet_grid(event ~ sex,
             scale = "free")
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_boxplot()`).

#2b The female runners have a higher median than the male runners in the 10 Mile event. The female runners again have a slightly higher median than the male runners in the 5K event. The difference in the median between males and females in greater in the 10 Mile event than in the 5K event. There was a wider range of results (the time taken to complete the race) in the 10 Mile event than in the 5K event.

Exercise 4

Example of a bad data visualisation

Image 1 is taken from a news article which is about global warming.

Matt McGrath/BBC, “Carbon emissions threaten 1.5C climate threshold sooner than thought - report” [Online]. Available at: https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-67242386 (Accessed: 03 NOvember 2023)

The above image presents a bad data visualisation because:

  • Reason 1 The reader cannot read any of the data specifically. This fault shows that it is a bad visualisation as it does not respect the people. There is too much data for the visualisation to be readable.
  • Reason 2 The years cannot be distinguished by the reader. This fault shows that it is a bad visualisation as it does not respect the data

Example of a good data visualisation

Image 2 is take from a news article about interest rates.

Kevin Peachey/BBC, “Interest rates: How the Bank of England’s decision affects you and your money” [Online]. Available at: https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-57764601 (Accessed: 03 November 2023)

The above image presents a good data visualisation because:

  • Reason 1 The reader can easy read the information, as it is clear and straightforward, showing that it respects the people. The reader needs very little knowlegde of graphs to understand the visualisation.
  • Reason 2 The visualisation has accurate and correct axis, showing a respect for data. The visualisation also respects the mathematics as the axis use an equal integer between the values.
